The company’s products include Nano-Tune Tunable Diode Laser: a diode laser system with a high resolution spectrometer that provides real-time monitoring and closed-loop control of the laser output; Nano-Stick Spectrometer (NS): a product based on DPH that allows for managing, processing, and guiding light inside miniature integrated optics devices; Nano-Clarity: the software for Nano-Stick Spectrometer that acquires and displays multiple spectra; and Nano-MCS: the software for Nano-Tune Tunable Laser that completes monitoring and control of laser and integral spectrometers. NOD devices are used for traditional types of spectroscopy such as emission, absorption, Raman, Laser Induced Breakdown Spectroscopy (LIBS), and more. Nano Optic Devices was founded in 2007 and is based in Santa Clara, California.

Full Description: Channel Films is the trading name of Channel Home Entertainment Ltd., based in London, UK.  Having originated in 1989 from a Video shop in Ladbroke Grove (Channel 142), the company grew to 8 outlets over the following 10 years, to become nationally recognized specialists in Cult, Classic & Foreign VHS/DVD.  Formed from a partnership between James Cooke, Paul Smith & Malcolm Wareing, the business (Channel Video Films) evolved and diversified into Mail-Order sales in 1992, specializing in the supply of Art House Films to University libraries and related Film collectors throughout the world.   This coincided with the development of one of the first Internet Mail Order operations, eventually evolving into a specialist digital delivery platform, in tandem with a sister technology company, Filmed Media.  Channel Films have downsized over the years to 4 Film Rental shops in Ladbroke Grove, Maida Vale, Queens Park and Camden Town, being the only London Chain remaining besides Blockbuster.  As the physical Film Rental sector has diminished, the business has continued to develop it's on-line presence in the Internet VOD sector, with access to independent content from around 15 distributors, via Filmed Media.

Description: Brewer And Pritchard is a law firm that specializes in a variety of fraud cases.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Houston Area, Southern US
Full Description: Founded in 1991 and based in Houston, Texas, the law firm of Brewer & Pritchard, PC, has embraced technology since the firm’s outset. It became the city’s first law practice, and one of the nation’s first, to institute telecommuting, which enabled staff members, including new parents, to work at home. Brewer & Pritchard pioneered the all-digital law library in Houston, commissioning a specially constructed CD-ROM tower in 1994. The following year, the leaders of the practice purchased a domain name to create the first active website for an area law firm. In addition, Brewer & Pritchard became paperless at the beginning of the millennium, long before state and federal courts mandated electronic filings. The firm’s attorneys possess expertise in a wide range of practice areas, including corporate and securities, mergers and acquisitions, real estate, construction, insurance, and product liability, as well as in general business and financial and commercial matters. Brewer & Pritchard handles all phases of initial public offerings, internal corporate organization, U.S. Securities & Exchange Commission filings, and state and federal reporting. For mergers and acquisitions, the attorneys assess and recommend the most advantageous business combinations; write letters of intent; prepare confidentiality, asset purchase, and stock-exchange agreements; and conduct due-diligence investigations. They perform all duties necessary to close transactions. Cofounder and Principal J. Mark Brewer has acted as Managing Director of the practice since its inception. Recognized world-wide for his litigation and resolution skills in high-rise commercial-building defect and design cases, he has worked in state, federal, and Judge Advocate General courts, and he has won numerous jury verdicts with awards in the multimillions. Cofounder Thomas C. Pritchard, who leads the practice areas of mergers and acquisitions and corporate/securities, has closed more than $400 million in financing for clients in his two-decade career. Brewer & Pritchard, which also includes principal Sondra Jones Jurica and several associate attorneys, has held the prestigious AV peer-review rating with Martindale-Hubbell every year since 1992. CV, BV and AV are registered certification marks of Reed Elsevier Properties Inc., used in accordance with the Martindale-Hubbell certification procedures, standards, and policies. For more information, visit www.martindale.com/Products_and_Services/Peer_Review_Ratings.aspx.

Description: SalesforceCAD focusses on mobilizing a borderless CAD network infrastructure to improve workflow between different CRM, CAD, and PDM tools.
Headquarters Regions: Midwestern US
Full Description: The Salesforce CAD project is about mobilizing a faster, more reliable,  borderless CAD network infrastructure for a more synergistic workflow between different CRM, CAD and PDM tools.    Our mission is more effective, efficient collaboration on data-driven complex engineering design and product launch projects.  Eliminating the barriers and optimizing constraints in rapid, efficient collaboration between ALL holders of critical engineering, manufacturing and marketing information for product launch and distribution will be the key to the success of this project.    We believe we can achieve our mission by leveraging existing CAD and cloud-based CRM technology with new developments from multi-player gaming technology and other data-intensive social networks.   Of course, there will also be other tools and methods that we exploit to boost the productivity of project engineering teams with affordable, real-time 3D collaboration and simulation, quantitative critical parameter management and data visualization.   Our approach is rooted in our belief that successful product launch is a matter of plugging in the power of all project engineering team interactions with customers representatives, R&D and lab partners, supply chain partners, manufacturing partners, marketing and distribution chain personnel and other launch-critical players involved in product development and launch.   If we can more effectively master the virtual CAD realm by understanding the criticality of customer requirements and supplier capabilities, fewer resources will be wasted on failed product launches.  The size and predictability of customer demand will improve by engaging key customer representatives much earlier in the development cycle.

Full Description: Triptonite is an ad-hoc, map based travel discovery platform, helping users to seek out and share travel ideas. At Triptonite we believe there is value in offering a sense of surprise and discovery when seeking out new travel destinations. Triptonite aims to be the very first website that folks think of when they want to explore a travel destination, before booking.   Triptonite can also help travelers find new places to visit - places they may never have considered before. People love to travel, they love to surf the web, and they love to watch TV.  Triptonite combines the interactivity of the web with the proven "passive" appeal of television delivering a  captivating website for exploring the world and discovering new travel destinations.  Triptonite fills the travel exploration, pre-planning niche with a discovery-based platform where people interactively select areas on a map display and watch geographic slideshows.   They can tag locations viewed in the slideshow and  share them with family and friends. Description: The Napkin Look & Feel is a pluggable Java look and feel that looks like it was scrawled on a napkin.
Headquarters Regions: Greater San Diego Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: The Napkin Look & Feel is a pluggable Java look and feel that looks like it was scrawled on a napkin. You can use it to make provisional work actually look provisional, or just for fun. It is released under a BSD-style license The idea is to try to develop a look and feel that can be used in Java applications that looks informal and provisional, yet be fully functional for development. Often when people see a GUI mock-up, or a complete GUI without full functionality, they assume that the code behind it is working. While this can be used to sleazy advantage, it can also convince people who ought to know better (like your managers) that you are already done when you have just barely begun, or when only parts are complete. No matter how much you speak to their rational side, the emotional response still says "Done!". Which after a while leads to a later question: "That was done months ago! What are they doing? Playing Quake?" A good article on this is Joel on Software's “The Iceberg Secret, Revealed”.
